{"word":"οἰκτρός","slug":"οἰκτρός","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>οἰκτρός</b></el> <el>(οἰκτρός, ή, όν) </el><br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:οἶκτος'><el>οἶκτος</el></a>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>pitiable, in piteous plight</i>, <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b>of things, <i>pitiable, piteous, lamentable</i>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b>in <a href='S:active signification'><a href='S:Active voice'>act.</a></a> sense, <i>piteous</i>, <b><a href='S:Odyssey'>Od.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>; <el>οἰκτρᾶς γόον ὄρνιθος</el>, of the nightingale, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>;—<a href='S:neuter'>neut.</a> <a href='S:plural'>pl.</a> as <a href='S:regular, regularly'>regul.</a> <a href='S:Adverb'>adv.</a> <el>οἰκτρῶς</el>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b> —Besides <a href='S:Comparative'>comp.</a> and <a href='S:Superlative'>Sup.</a> <el>οἰκτρότερος, -τατος</el>, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b> has an <a href='S:irregular'>irreg.</a> <a href='S:Superlative'>Sup.</a> <el>οἴκτιστος</el> (<a href='S:quod vide'>q. <a href='S:vide'>v.</a></a>).<p/></div>"}]}